Note that the gain is proportional to the ratio between arithmetic
and geometric means of the transform coefficient variances.
(Note similarities to the spectral flatness measure.)
The factor <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>γ</m:mi><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:msub><m:mo>/</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>γ</m:mi><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> accounts for changes in distribution
which affect uniform-quantizer efficiency.
For example, if <emphasis effect="bold">T</emphasis> caused uniformly distributed <emphasis effect="italics">x</emphasis> to become
Gaussian distributed <emphasis effect="italics">y<sub>k</sub></emphasis>, <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>γ</m:mi><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:msub><m:mo>/</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>γ</m:mi><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> would contribute a 7 dB
loss in TC-to-PCM performance.
If, on the other hand, <emphasis effect="italics">x</emphasis> was Gaussian, then <emphasis effect="italics">y<sub>k</sub></emphasis> would also be
Gaussian and <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>γ</m:mi><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:msub><m:mo>/</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>γ</m:mi><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math>.
